The Delaunay triangulation of a point process $\xi$ is the dual graph of the associated Voronoi tiling. In this article, conditions on a simple, stationary, isotropic point process are given under which the variable speed random walk on the Delaunay triangulation—that is, the Markov chain that has a unit transition rate along each edge of the graph—satisfies a quenched invariance principle, i.e. for almost-realisation of the point process, the random walk converges to Brownian motion under the usual diffusive scaling (a similar result is also noted for the discrete-time simple random walk). More specifically, the conditions on the point process are as follows: (V) only small boxes not hit by $\xi$; (SD) stochastic domination of the collection of `good boxes', where the number of points in $\xi$ is well behaved, by a Bernoulli site percolation process; (Er) ergodicity of $\xi$ under translations; and (PM) polynomial moments for certain quantities, such as the number of points of $\xi$ in a unit volume. Alternative conditions are also provided, and it is also noted that they are readily checked for homogeneous Poisson processes, Mat{\'{e}}rn cluster processes, and Mat{\'{e}}rn hardcore processes. The proof is based on the now standard approach for proving quenched invariance principles involving the construction of a (sub-linear) harmonic corrector, which enables the result to be obtained from a classical invariance principle for martingales. Reviewed by David A. Croydon},
