@incollection{Kendall-2014d,
abstract = {{\textcopyright} 2015 John Wiley {\&} Sons, Ltd. All rights reserved.The use of barycentres in data analysis is illustrated, using as an example a dataset of hurricane trajectories. The trajectories are modelled as sequences of points on the sphere (using "best track" data from the HURDAT2 dataset). Sphere barycentres are combined with a (k)-means algorithm to classify the hurricanes; temporalassociation is then investigated using simple non-parametric statistical techniques.},
address = {Chichester},
annote = {From Mathematical Reviews:
This paper is the seventh chapter in Kanti Mardia's Festschrift [Geometry driven statistics, Wiley Ser. Probab. Stat., Wiley, Chichester, 2015; MR3470148]. The work stems from an `intellectual curiosity' as to whether two hurricanes that occur consecutively exhibit similar behaviour, in a geometric sense. The chapter offers an interesting methodological contribution, one that combines unsupervised learning with non-parametric statistics for discovering temporal associations (or dependence) in repeated, classified, time-series data. 
   After providing some background on barycentres, specifically Riemannian barycentres and cosine-barycentres, in Section 7.2, the author proceeds to describe the HURDAT2 dataset on hurricane trajectories, which inspires the methodology developed in the later sections. He eventually uses 179 North Atlantic hurricane trajectories from this dataset, which occurred in 37 years between 1950 and 2012 (years with two or fewer hurricanes are omitted). 
   The bulk of the methodology is presented in Section 7.4. First, the hurricane trajectories are clustered into k=20 clusters using a k-means algorithm. The k-means algorithm minimises the within-cluster sum of cosine distances, so that the cluster centroids are the barycentre centroids of the clusters. Once clustered, temporal association is assessed using the test statistic T=∑yTy, where 
Ty(x1,{\ldots},xhy)=∑i=2hyI[Xy,i=Xy,i−1],
Xy,i is the cluster of the ith hurricane (ordered according to time) in year y, and hy is the number of hurricanes in year y. 
   Second, the author makes a connection between Ty and the one-dimensional Potts model. He uses this relationship to approximate the mean and the variance of T (conditioned on the number of hurricanes per cluster per year) under the null hypothesis of no temporal association. An extension to allow for geometric temporal decay in association is also proposed. 
   Results, presented in Section 7.5, show that the normal approximation to the conditional distribution of T is adequate in practice. The author concedes that the rejection of the null hypothesis in the analysis of the North Atlantic hurricane trajectories is somewhat sensitive to the choice of hurricanes that were chosen for this study. In addition, the hypothesis test is implicitly dependent on the use of the k-means algorithm and the number of clusters k. Nonetheless, it is the overall framework, and not the specifics, that is appealing in this chapter. The work provides a methodological foundation for studying temporal associations in trajectory data that are classified according to some domain-specific criteria. 
